<HEAD>Chinese Premier Invites Japan's Emperor To China</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 9 grafs after 6th pvs, ``The official...'' to ADD background
on Chinese-Japanese hostility. No Pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese Premier <PERSON>Li Peng</PERSON> met <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s emperor and
empress today and invited them to visit <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>, government officials
said.
   Li made the invitation during a 20-minute meeting with the newly
enthroned monarch at the <ORGANIZATION>Tokyo Imperial Palace</ORGANIZATION>, a senior <ORGANIZATION>Imperial
Household Agency</ORGANIZATION> official said.
   If the invitation is accepted, Emperor <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> would be the
first Japanese monarch to visit <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>.
   But the palace spokesman said several problems exist and the
visit would have to await the end of a year of court mourning for
<PERSON>Akihito</PERSON>'s father, Emperor <PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON>, who died on <DATE>Jan. 7</DATE> at age 87.
   ``Premier <PERSON>Li</PERSON> said that he hoped the royal couple would visit
when the time was right for them. In reply, the emperor thanked him
but said the decision must be made by the government,'' said the
agency official.
   The official, who briefed reporters on condition of anonymity,
said the two also discussed ``their nations' 2,000-year history,
including World War II.''
   Bitter memories of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s actions during World War II often
have clouded Japan-China relations. After sharp criticism by <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>
and other nations, Prime Minister <PERSON>Noboru Takeshita</PERSON> in <DATE>February</DATE>
retrated a statement that future historians must decide whether
<LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> was an aggressor.
   More than 10 million Chinese died during <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s 1937-45
invasion of the Chinese mainland. Beijing reacts strongly to any
Japanese attempt to deny responsibility.
   Japanese news reports have speculated that <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> would express
regret over <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s militarist past during today's meeting, but
government officials refused to confirm or deny this.
   ``The emperor expressed his views on the nations' pasts, and Li
welcomed those views,'' said the official.
   Earlier today, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> announced it would lend <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> up to <MONEY>$734
million</MONEY> in the current fiscal year. The loan is to help fund 11
projects for modernization in <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>, including an expansion of
ports in <LOCATION>Lianyungang</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Qingdao</LOCATION> and construction of a subway in
<LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION>.
   Li is on a five-day official visit to <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> accompanied by
senior officials, including Foreign Minister <PERSON>Qian Qichen</PERSON>, who met
today with his Japanese counterpart, <ORGANIZATION>Sousuke Uno</ORGANIZATION>.
   The last Chinese premier to visit <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> was <PERSON>Zhao Ziyang</PERSON>, now
head of <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Communist Party</ORGANIZATION>, in <DATE>May 1982</DATE>.
</TEXT>
