<H3> <TI>   Japan's Emperor Grants Audience to Banker </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japan's Emperor Grants Audience to Banker </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704150594 Taipei CNA in English 0807 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704150594 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<FÊP=106> [By <LOCATION>Sofia</LOCATION> Wu] </F>
  [Text] <LOCATION>Taipei</LOCATION>, <DATE>April 7</DATE> (CNA) -- <PERSON>Jeffrey Ku</PERSON>, chairman of 
the Taipei-based <ORGANIZATION>Chinatrust Commercial Bank</ORGANIZATION>, was granted an 
audience with Japanese Emperor <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> [6 <DATE>April</DATE>]. 
  "I feel honored to have met with the Japanese emperor at his 
<LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> palace," <PERSON>Ku</PERSON> said <DATE>Thursday</DATE> upon his return from a five-day 
visit to <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>. 
  Ku, also an unpaid advisor to <LOCATION>Taiwan</LOCATION>'s Executive Yuan, 
stressed that his visit to <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> was private. 
  Ku said Emperor <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> expressed his goodwill and regard 
for 
<LOCATION>Taiwan</LOCATION>. "<PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> was interested in <LOCATION>Taiwan</LOCATION>'s current 
developments," he noted. 
  Ku said he briefed the Japanese emperor on <LOCATION>Taiwan</LOCATION>'s economic 
strength and its role in Southeast Asian economic development. 
  "We also exchanged views on the possible impact on <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION> of 
the <ORGANIZATION>North American Free Trade Agreement</ORGANIZATION> and the prospects for 
the formation of the proposed <ORGANIZATION>East Asia Economic Caucus</ORGANIZATION> and the 
Asian Free Trade Agreement," <PERSON>Ku</PERSON> said. 
  Ku was the first <LOCATION>Taiwan</LOCATION> businessman granted a formal 
audience 
with <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> since the emperor took the throne in <DATE>October 1989</DATE>. 
Akihito talked briefly with [passage indistinct]. 
  Political observers said <PERSON>Jeffrey Ku</PERSON>'s meeting with <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> 
would boost the development of substantive ties between <LOCATION>Taiwan</LOCATION> 
and <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, even though the Japanese emperor is just a spiritual 
leader and wields no political power. 
  <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> recognizes <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> and has been reluctant to develop 
any official ties with <LOCATION>Taiwan</LOCATION> for fear of offending communist 
Chinese leaders. 
  Many countries, including the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> and 
<LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>, have sent ministerial-level officials to visit <LOCATION>Taiwan</LOCATION>, 
but <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> has not followed suit. 

</TEXT>

