<HEAD>Emperor Visits Bomb Memorial With Nagasaki Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAGASAKI, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> today became the first
Japanese monarch to pay tribute at a monument to the 70,000 people
who died in the atomic bomb blast that devastated <LOCATION>Nagasaki</LOCATION> 45 years
ago.
   A steady rain fell as <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON>, accompanied by <ORGANIZATION>Empress Michiko</ORGANIZATION>,
bowed deeply and placed a bouquet of white flowers on a dark
granite cenotaph before the monument.
   Mayor <PERSON>Hitoshi Motoshima</PERSON> led <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> to the site. <PERSON>Motoshima</PERSON> was
shot in the chest in <DATE>January</DATE> by an ultrarightist for saying the
late Emperor <PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON> could have helped end World War II sooner and
spared <LOCATION>Nagasaki</LOCATION>.
   <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> surrendered six days after the <DATE>Aug. 9, 1945</DATE> atomic bombing.
   Though <PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON>, now known in <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> as <LOCATION>Emperor Showa</LOCATION>, visited
<LOCATION>Nagasaki</LOCATION> for a sporting event in <DATE>1969</DATE>, his son, <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON>, is the
first emperor to present flowers at the Peace Park memorial.
   As the emperor left the park, some of the 2,600 people who
attended sang ``<PERSON>Kimi Ga Yo</PERSON>,'' <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s unofficial national anthem.
Shouts of ``Banzai,'' a wish for long life, rang out when his
20-car motorcade arrived.
   ``The emperor is from a new generation, my generation,'' said
<PERSON>Sachiko Nagata</PERSON>, a store clerk who was seven years old when the bomb
fell. ``I think he has helped heal some of the wounds of the war by
coming here.''
   Police mobilized 4,000 officers to provide security for the
emperor and empress during their four-day visit to the city on the
southern island of <LOCATION>Kyushu</LOCATION>.
   The Roman Catholic mayor drew the ire of rightist groups with
his remarks about <PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON>. Before being shot, <PERSON>Motoshima</PERSON> received
countless death threats and lost his membership in the governing
Liberal Democratic Party.
   Japanese rightists represent a small minority but maintain a
high profile, dressing in military garb and driving through cities
in convoys of armored, painted trucks blaring march music. They are
staunchly nationalist.
   They also revere the monarchy and chastise those they believe
oppose it.
</TEXT>
