<HEAD>New Japanese Emperor A Product of Postwar Age</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Japan-Entronement, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> has long lived in the shadow of his
father, the late <PERSON>Emperor Hirohito</PERSON>, and the memories of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s
headlong march into the <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION> War that <PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON>'s name evoked.
   But now that <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> has assumed the throne left by his father's
death, many Japanese are looking to him as the symbol of a new age
- that of the generation who experienced war as children and
rebuilt the nation in peace.
   <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> was 11 at the end of World War II, which Japanese
militarists had urged the nation into in the name of his father.
   The impact of surrender and reform under the guidance of
U.S.-led occupation forces deeply affected his youth.
   Before <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> turned 13, <PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON> made his historic
renunciation of imperial divinity.
   Occupation troops departed <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> in <DATE>1952</DATE>, leaving behind them a
democratic constitution that renounced war and defined <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s
monarchs as ``symbols,'' not the priest-kings of bygone days.
   That imperial role seems to fit <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON>, who in one of his first
duties after assuming the throne upon the death of <PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON> in
<DATE>January 1989</DATE> promised to uphold the constitution ``along with the
people.''
   Akihito, born <DATE>Dec. 23, 1933</DATE>, bears a strong physical resemblance
to <PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON>, and has inherited his father's short, almost frail,
build. He also has his father's passion for science, and is a
respected scholar in the study of gobies, a type of mud-sucking
fish.
   Akihito speaks fluent English and is <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s most widely
traveled emperor. He has made official visits to 37 countries, his
first to <LOCATION>England</LOCATION> for the coronation of <ORGANIZATION>Queen Elizabeth II</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1953</DATE>.
   Reflecting the circumstances of his upbringing, <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> is often
described by former schoolmates and palace officials as a more
democratically-minded, warmer person than the quiet, reclusive
<PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON>.
   He has also been far more prone to set his own precedents.
   Just three years after completing his education - <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> was
the first emperor schooled alongside commoners - the royal heir
chose a commoner for his bride, making another break from the past.
   The woman, <PERSON>Michiko Shoda</PERSON>, was the daughter of one of the
nation's wealthiest businessmen, but their marriage in <DATE>1959</DATE> sent
shock waves through <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s former nobility.
   To the rest of the nation, however, the wedding was welcomed as
none before. About 500,000 people lined the streets for a chance to
see <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> and <LOCATION>Michiko</LOCATION> in their horse-drawn carriage during a
parade after the ceremony.
   The royal couple again broke with tradition by raising their own
children, a decision prompted in part by <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON>'s desire to have
the family life he was denied as a child, according to <PERSON>Minoru
Hamao</PERSON>, a former imperial chamberlain.
   Taken away from his parents at an early age to be raised by
strangers, <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> at times complained of the loneliness he felt
when his classmates would talk to him about their homes, said
<PERSON>Hamao</PERSON>, who served <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> for two decades.
   Akihito's first child and heir, <PERSON>Crown Prince Naruhito</PERSON>, was born
<DATE>Feb. 23, 1960</DATE>. They have another son, <PERSON>Prince Akishino</PERSON>, and
daughter, <ORGANIZATION>Princess Nori</ORGANIZATION>.
   Though the crown prince remains single, Prince <PERSON>Akishino</PERSON> earlier
this year wed <PERSON>Kiko Kawashima</PERSON> - who, like the empress, had no royal
lineage.
</TEXT>
