  [Text] <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, <DATE>March 26</DATE> KYODO -- South Korean President <PERSON>Kim 
Yong-sam</PERSON> renewed his hope <DATE>Saturday</DATE> [26 <DATE>March</DATE>] for the visit to 
<LOCATION>South Korea</LOCATION> by <PERSON>Emperor Akihito</PERSON> and <PERSON>Empress Michiko</PERSON>, a senior 
<ORGANIZATION>Imperial Household Agency</ORGANIZATION> official said. Kim, before departing 
for <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> after a three-day visit to <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, extended the 
invitation again to the imperial couple as they bid farewell to 
<PERSON>Kim</PERSON> and his wife Son Myong-sun at the <ORGANIZATION>Akasaka Palace</ORGANIZATION>, said 
<PERSON>Kiyoshi Sumiya</PERSON>, the agency's grand master of ceremonies. 
  Kim told the couple during the 20-minute meeting that he 
wishes to invite them to visit <LOCATION>South Korea</LOCATION> at a proper time. 
  During an audience at the imperial palace on <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, the 
president officially invited <PERSON>Emperor Akihito</PERSON> and Empress Michiko 
to visit <LOCATION>South Korea</LOCATION> to forge a new future-oriented 
relationship. At that time, the emperor replied the Japanese 
Government would decide on whether he will go to <LOCATION>South Korea</LOCATION>. 
  The visit by <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s monarch, however, is still a sensitive 
issue in <LOCATION>South Korea</LOCATION>, which was under Japanese colonial rule 
from <DATE>1910</DATE> to <DATE>1945</DATE>. 
  During his stay in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Kim</PERSON> urged <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> to work together 
to 
solve <LOCATION>North Korea</LOCATION>'s suspected nuclear weapons development 
program, which has heightened tension on the Korean peninsula, 
and stressed the importance of forward-looking bilateral 
relations. 

</TEXT>

