<HEAD>Roh Invites Japanese Emperor To Make First Visit to Korea</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK3</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Roh returning home,
clarifies Akihito, Kaifu comment, changes byline. Pickup 8th graf
pvs, `About 20,000...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President <PERSON>Roh</PERSON> Tae-woo <DATE>today</DATE> said ``no
amount of apology can be fully satisfactory'' for <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s brutal
colonization of <LOCATION>Korea</LOCATION>, but that <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s expressions of regret are
the basis for a new relationship.
   Roh returned today from a three-day trip to <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, during which
he invited Emperor Akihito to make the first Japanese imperial
visit to <LOCATION>South Korea</LOCATION>.
   The invitation came after <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> expressed regret for the
colonization of <LOCATION>Korea</LOCATION> nearly half a century ago, and Japanese Prime
Minister <PERSON>Toshiki Kaifu</PERSON> extended ``honest apologies'' for Korean
suffering in the colonial period.
   Roh, upon his arrival in <LOCATION>Seoul</LOCATION>, said it was time for the two
countries to put the past behind them.
   ``Even if we may feel that the Japanese apologies do not fully
live up to our expectations, we should accept them with magnanimity
and generosity, now that <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> has forthrightly admitted its
mistakes,'' he said at an airport news conference.
   During the colonial period, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> tried to stifle Korean culture
by banning Koreans from learning their language and forcing them to
adoptJapanese names. Tens of thousands of <LOCATION>Koreans</LOCATION> were killed after
being drafted for the Japanese war efforts.
   ``I well understand what feelings my fellow countrymen have
about what went on between our country and <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> in the past. No
amount of apology can be fully satisfactory,'' <PERSON>Roh</PERSON> said.
   Some <PERSON>Koreans</PERSON> said Japanese measures to clear up current sore
points were more important than apologizing for the past.
   There are unresolved disputes over discrimination against
<LOCATION>Koreans</LOCATION> living in <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, aid to <LOCATION>Koreans</LOCATION> who remain displaced after
being forcibly removed from their homeland to perform wartime labor
for <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, and assistance to Korean survivors of the atomic
bombings of <LOCATION>Hiroshima</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Nagasaki</LOCATION>.
   <PERSON>Roh</PERSON> said he had asked <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> to move forward on these issues and
expressed satisfaction with the progress made so far.
   About 20,000 police had been mobilized in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> to provide
security for <PERSON>Roh</PERSON> during his three-day state visit against possible
threats from extreme leftist or rightist groups. But no incidents
were reported.
   Roh's visit to <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> was only the second by a South Korean head
of state since the two countries established diplomatic relations
in <DATE>1965</DATE>. Roh's predecessor, <PERSON>Chun Doo-hwan</PERSON>, visited <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> in <DATE>1984</DATE>.
   <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Korea</LOCATION> have a long history of enmity and sore points
still linger from <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s 1910-45 colonization of the <LOCATION>Korean
Peninsula</LOCATION>.
   The centerpiece of <PERSON>Roh</PERSON>'s visit was the <DATE>Thursday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> state
banquet at which <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> expressed his ``deepest regret'' for the
suffering Koreans endured at Japanese hands. Kaifu offered his
``sincere remorse and honest apologies,'' and said good relations
between <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Korea</LOCATION> are a basis for peace in the region.
   Roh extended the invitation to <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Empress Michiko</ORGANIZATION> to
visit <LOCATION>South Korea</LOCATION> during a short meeting with the emperor today at
the <ORGANIZATION>Akasaka State Guesthouse</ORGANIZATION>, said a palace official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   ``After your coronation I am sure that you will visit many
countries, and I hope that you will consider visiting <LOCATION>South Korea</LOCATION>
also,'' the official quoted <PERSON>Roh</PERSON> as saying.
   Akihito, who assumed the throne after the death of his father,
Emperor <PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON>, will not travel abroad until after his official
coronation on <DATE>Nov. 12</DATE>. The coronation is traditionally delayed by a
year of mourning for the deceased emperor.
   Akihito would be the first emperor to visit <LOCATION>South Korea</LOCATION> since
its creation after <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s defeat in World War II.
   Japanese <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Taizo Watanabe</PERSON> said <PERSON>Kaifu</PERSON>
had also accepted an invitation from <PERSON>Roh</PERSON> to visit <LOCATION>South Korea</LOCATION> at a
mutually convenient time.
</TEXT>
