<HEAD>Radicals Set Off Bombs as Throng Cheers the Emperor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100,000 people thronged to the Imperial
Palace on <DATE>Sunday</DATE> to cheer newly enthroned <PERSON>Emperor Akihito</PERSON>, but
radicals set off several bombs near a shrine he is to visit.
   Akihito, <PERSON>Empress Michiko</PERSON> and other royal family members,
protected by bulletproof glass, came out onto the palace balcony
eight times during the day to greet the well-wishers, which the
<ORGANIZATION>Imperial Household Agency</ORGANIZATION> numbered at 109,800.
   Loud shouts of ``Long live the emperor!'' rang through the
palace courtyard as he finished his short statement giving thanks
to the crowds.
   Akihito became emperor immediately after his father, Emperor
<PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON>, died in <DATE>January 1989</DATE>. His formal enthronement <DATE>Nov. 12</DATE>
followed a mourning period. Enthronement-related ceremonies are to
continue into <DATE>December</DATE>.
   At least four explosions occurred <DATE>Sunday</DATE> near the <LOCATION>Grand Shrines</LOCATION>
of Ise, 180 miles southwest of <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, which <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> is to visit
next week, said an official of <ORGANIZATION>Mie Prefectural Police</ORGANIZATION> who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   No injuries or major damage were reported in the explosions, two
of which occurred at the Ujiyamada railway station and two along a
railway track near the station.
   The emperor and empress are to use the railroad when they travel
to Ise to pray to the sun goddess on <DATE>Nov. 27-28</DATE>. <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s line of
emperors is said to have descended from the sun goddess <ORGANIZATION>Amaterasu</ORGANIZATION>.
   Radicals claimed responsibility for dozens of explosions and
fires in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> during <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON>'s enthronement. None caused serious
injuries.
   The radicals oppose the monarchy as a remnant of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s prewar
imperialism.
</TEXT>
