<F P=103> SK0102060594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul HANGUK ILBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In a meeting with reporters on 31 <DATE>January</DATE>, Kong 
No-myong, <ORGANIZATION>ROK</ORGANIZATION> ambassador to <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, said: "It is time to hold 
full-scale discussions on ROK-Japanese cultural exchanges based 
on personnel exchanges. Particularly in this <LOCATION>Visit Korea</LOCATION> Year, 
the government must reexamine its tourist policy to induce 
Japanese tourists, who patronize <ORGANIZATION>ROK</ORGANIZATION> tourism the most, and 
consider adding Chinese characters to Korean signs." 
  Ambassador Kong, who returned home temporarily to attend the 
overseas mission chiefs meeting to be held here beginning 2 
<DATE>February</DATE>, said that our people should abandon their "new policy 
of seclusion" [saeroun swoeguk chongchaek] for 
internationalization and opening up. 
  The following are questions and answers from the meeting 
between Ambassador Kong and reporters: 
  [Unidentified reporter] Some people point out that it is too 
early for the <ORGANIZATION>ROK</ORGANIZATION> to exchange mass culture [taejung munhwa] with 
<LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> in view of the present indiscriminate infiltration of 
Japanese culture. 
  [Kong No-myong] Japanese books, video tapes, and television 
programs from satellite broadcasting services are now virtually 
opened to us. We should publicly introduce high-quality mass 
culture instead of overlooking its unlawful infiltration. An 
agreement on the general opening of mass cultural markets was 
reached in ROK-Japanese summit talks held <DATE>last year</DATE>, but the 
details of this issue have yet to be discussed. Accordingly, we 
have to hurry to take active measures. 
  [Reporter] What are the main agenda items to be discussed 
during President <PERSON>Kim Yong-sam</PERSON>'s visit to <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> in <DATE>March</DATE>? 
  [Kong] There is no pending political issue. Issues on 
economic cooperation between the <ORGANIZATION>ROK</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, such as mutual 
cooperative relations in preparation for the <LOCATION>Uruguay</LOCATION> Round 
treaty and methods to vitalize the ROK-Japanese Industrial and 
<ORGANIZATION>Technological Cooperation Committee</ORGANIZATION>, will be discussed. 
  [Reporter] Will President <PERSON>Kim</PERSON> meet Japanese Emperor <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> 
when he visits <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>? Will the Japanese emperor visit the <ORGANIZATION>ROK</ORGANIZATION>? 
  [Kong] As his <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> visit is a state visit, President <PERSON>Kim</PERSON> 
will probably meet the Japanese emperor. If the Japanese 
emperor visits the <ORGANIZATION>ROK</ORGANIZATION>, it would be a significant event. The 
decision on the date of his <ORGANIZATION>ROK</ORGANIZATION> visit is a domestic affairs 
matter and must be made prudently. 
  [Reporter] Does the North Korean nuclear issue have any 
relation to the establishment of diplomatic relations between 
<LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>North Korea</LOCATION>? 
  [Kong] <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> is willing to resume negotiations with <LOCATION>North 
Korea</LOCATION> whenever it wants. <LOCATION>North Korea</LOCATION>, however, has not yet made 
any noteworthy sign. <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> says that the resolution of the 
North Korean nuclear issue is not a prerequisite [chonje chogon] 
for Japanese-North Korean negotiations on establishment of 
diplomatic ties, although the nuclear issue is important. 

</TEXT>

