<HEAD>Emperor Akihito Pays Tribute to Nagasaki Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NAG1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAGASAKI, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For more than four decades, the bitter
memories of war and defeat clung to <PERSON>Emperor Hirohito</PERSON>. That same
ghost now haunts his son, <PERSON>Emperor Akihito</PERSON>, who on <DATE>Friday</DATE> paid
tribute to <LOCATION>Nagasaki</LOCATION>'s atomic bomb victims.
   About 3,800 people stood in steady rain as <LOCATION>Akihito</LOCATION>, accompanied
by <PERSON>Empress Michiko</PERSON>, became the first monarch to remember the
devastating <DATE>Aug. 9, 1945</DATE> attack at a monument to its 70,000 victims.
   The emperor bowed and placed a bouquet of white flowers on a
dark granite cenotaph before the Peace Park monument.
   The royal couple was greeted by loud yells of ``Banzai'' _ a
wish for long life _ when they arrived for the ceremony. And as
they left, some in the crowd sang ``<PERSON>Kimi Ga Yo</PERSON>,'' <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s
unofficial national anthem.
   The emperor and empress later visited a hospital for patients
suffering from illness related to the bombing.
   In a statement, <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> said that seeing the park and hospital
``renewed my thoughts for peace ... and prayers for those who still
are in pain because of the bomb's effects.''
   In <LOCATION>Nagasaki</LOCATION>, that pain runs deep.
   ``I think he has helped heal some of the wounds by coming,''
said store clerk <PERSON>Sachiko Nagata</PERSON>, who was seven years old when the
bomb was dropped and now suffers from radiation sickness.
   ``But it took too long for him to come to this park,'' she said.
   Though the late <PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON> visited <LOCATION>Nagasaki</LOCATION> for a sporting event
in <DATE>1969</DATE>, his son, <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON>, is the first emperor to present flowers
at the Peace Park memorial.
   Mayor <PERSON>Hitoshi Motoshima</PERSON> was the emperor's guide on the first of
his four-day visit to southern <LOCATION>Kyushu Island</LOCATION>. Motoshima was shot in
<DATE>January</DATE> by an ultra-rightist for saying <PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON> bore some
responsibilty for the war.
   <PERSON>Motoshima</PERSON> made the comment at a city assembly meeting in
<DATE>December 1988</DATE>, as <PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON> lay dying of the cancer that ended his
life one month later.
   The mayor also said <PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON> could have helped end the war
sooner and saved <LOCATION>Nagasaki</LOCATION> from the atomic bomb. <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> surrendered
six days after the attack.
   Though many Japanese share <PERSON>Motoshima</PERSON>'s opinions, his candor
angered ultra-rightist groups. For more than a year, he received
death threats.
   Since the shooting, <PERSON>Motoshima</PERSON> has become a symbol of freedom of
speech.
   Though the mayor described <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> as a ``wonderful human
being,'' he also said the monarch should strive to understand and
heal the wounds of the past.
   ``I hope the new emperor will reflect on why that war occured,
and use his position to further peace,'' <PERSON>Motoshima</PERSON> said <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   Akihito's freedom to publicly reflect on the war will be tested
three days after his visit to <LOCATION>Nagasaki</LOCATION> ends, when he is to meet
South Korean President <PERSON>Roh</PERSON> Tae-woo in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>.
   The question of how, or even if, <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> should apologize for
<LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s colonization of <LOCATION>Korea</LOCATION> from <DATE>1911</DATE> to the end of World War II
has become a major political issue between the neighbors.
   Though Prime Minister <PERSON>Toshiki Kaifu</PERSON> has said he plans to
apologize as the elected representative of the Japanese people,
several South Korean officials have reportedly demanded <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON>
make the apology.
   But many Japanese officials say such a ``political'' statement
by the emperor would violate the spirit of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s constitution,
which they say aims to limit imperial power by keeping the emperor
off the political stage.
</TEXT>
