<H3> <TI>   ROK President, Delegation Pay Three-Day Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Kim Invites Emperor To Visit ROK </H4>
<F P=102> OW2403113094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1108 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2403113094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, <DATE>March 24</DATE> KYODO -- South Korean President <PERSON>Kim 
Yong-sam</PERSON> on <DATE>Thursday</DATE> [24 <DATE>March</DATE>] officially invited <PERSON>Emperor 
Akihito</PERSON> and Empress Michiko to visit <LOCATION>South Korea</LOCATION> to forge a new 
future-oriented relationship, the <ORGANIZATION>Imperial Household Agency</ORGANIZATION> 
said. "I would like to promote relations between <LOCATION>South Korea</LOCATION> 
and <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> from a forward-looking, future-oriented view," a 
senior <ORGANIZATION>Imperial Palace</ORGANIZATION> official quoted Kim as saying. 
  Bilateral relations are still overshadowed by <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s 
colonial rule of the Korean peninsula from <DATE>1910</DATE> to <DATE>1945</DATE>, and 
anti-Japanese sentiment continues to run high. 
  Kim and his wife, Son Myong-sun, had a 25-minute audience 
with the imperial couple in an "overall pleasant atmosphere," 
<PERSON>Kiyoshi Sumiya</PERSON>, grand master of ceremonies, said. 
  "I think it would benefit our friendly neighborly relations 
if we could welcome the emperor and the empress in <LOCATION>South Korea</LOCATION>. 
I would like to seize this good opportunity to offer an 
invitation," <PERSON>Kim</PERSON> told the imperial couple. 
  The emperor replied it is the Japanese Government's decision 
on whether he goes abroad. 
  In an interview ahead of the visit, <PERSON>Kim</PERSON>, who was elected 
last 
year to a single five-year term, said he believes he will be 
able to receive the emperor in <LOCATION>Seoul</LOCATION> during his term in office. 
  The emperor told Kim it is important that both nations 
deepen 
their exchange while reflecting on history and respecting each 
other's cultures. 
  During colonization, <LOCATION>Koreans</LOCATION> were forbidden from speaking 
Korean in public and had to adopt Japanese names. In addition, 
<LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s forced recruitment of tens of thousands of Korean women 
for wartime military brothels has refueled bitter memories. 

</TEXT>

