<H3> <TI>   Japan's Hata Meets With Mitterand </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japan's Hata Meets With Mitterand </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0405163194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1557 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0405163194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION>, <DATE>May 4</DATE> KYODO -- Japanese Prime Minister 
<PERSON>Tsutomu Hata</PERSON> and French President <PERSON>Francois Mitterrand</PERSON> agreed 
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE> [4 May] that <LOCATION>North Korea</LOCATION>'s suspected nuclear weapons 
program threatens the global move toward preventing the spread 
of nuclear weapons to non-nuclear powers. 
  The two leaders shared the understanding during a two-hour 
meeting at the French Presidential Palace, Japanese officials 
said. 
  The meeting took place after Hata arrived in <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION> from <LOCATION>Rome</LOCATION> 
as part of his European tour, which will also take him to 
<LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Belgium</LOCATION>. 
  They said <PERSON>Hata</PERSON> told <PERSON>Mitterrand</PERSON> that the North Korean nuclear 
issue "is a serious problem that threatens the nuclear 
nonproliferation regime, as well as undermines the security of 
the Asia-Pacific region." 
  Hata also said, "we must counter the threat in solidarity, 
while keeping the channels for (diplomatic) dialogue open." 
  Mitterrand agreed with Hata's view, the Japanese officials 
said. 
  On <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Hata</PERSON> told <PERSON>Mitterrand</PERSON>, "it is important for <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> 
to 
provide greater transparency in its activities in the military 
field...and it is crucial for us to urge <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> to demonstrate a 
positive response in the field of human rights." 
  Hata also told <PERSON>Mitterrand</PERSON>, "<LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> wants to step up its 
cooperation with <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> in various fields from now on" to build 
a new international order to secure global peace in addition to 
strengthening the capabilities of the <ORGANIZATION>United Nations</ORGANIZATION>, the 
officials said. 
  Mitterrand replied, "I agree with your view. The two nations 
can build up a stronger relationship of cooperation." 
  The French president expressed his interest in enhancing 
cooperation, particularly in extending economic assistance to 
such areas as <LOCATION>Indochina</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION>. 
  Hata expressed gratitude for <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>'s endorsement for 
<LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s 
bid to secure a permanent seat on the <ORGANIZATION>UN Security Council</ORGANIZATION>, of 
which <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> is one of the five permanent members. 
  French Foreign Minister <PERSON>Alain Juppe</PERSON> expressed his support 
for 
<LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s bid for permanent membership on the <ORGANIZATION>UN</ORGANIZATION> decision-making 
body during his visit to <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> in <DATE>March</DATE>. 
  Mitterrand, however, stopped short of addressing the issue, 
according to the Japanese officials. 
  The French leader expressed his nation's readiness to 
welcome 
Japanese Emperor <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> and his wife <PERSON>Michiko</PERSON>, who are slated to 
visit <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> in <DATE>October</DATE>. 
  "We are looking forward to meeting the emperor and empress," 
the president was quoted as saying. 
  Hata replied, "the emperor is also looking forward to the 
visit." The royal couple is slated to visit <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> on 
a two-week trip that will begin in late <DATE>September</DATE>. 

</TEXT>

