<HEAD>President Lauds Japanese Emperor For Role In Ending WWII</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>WASHINGTON</LOCATION> _ President <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> mourned the death of <PERSON>Emperor
Hirohito</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, saying he played ``a truly heroic role'' in
ending World War II hostilities between his country and the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION>.
   ``On behalf of the people and government of the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, we
extend our deepest condolences to His Imperial Majesty, the Emperor,
to the Imperial family, and to the People of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>,'' the president
said in a statement released by the <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> shortly after the
annoucement of the emperor's death <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> said the emperor's 62-year reign ``spanned one of the most
tumultuous, and yet at the same time constructive eras in the
history of mankind _ an age of unprecedented economic collapse, a
most vicious war, astonishing scientific acheivement, and dramatic
political and social changes throughout the world.''
   ``It was also an era of unprecedented reconciliation. His majesty
played a truly heroic role in bringing hostilities between our two
peoples to an end and leading the Japanese people through a period
of reconstruction and reconciliation that has resulted in both the
prosperity the Japanese know today and in the close relations our
two nations and peoples now enjoy,'' <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> said.
   The president recalled the late emperor had visited the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION> in <DATE>1975</DATE>, and that he and his wife <PERSON>Nancy</PERSON> had ``enjoyed several
meetings with him, most recently in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>'' in <DATE>1986</DATE>. The statement
also noted the first couple had entertained the former Crown Prince
<PERSON>Akihito</PERSON> and <PERSON>Crown Princess Michiko</PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1987</DATE>.
   ``While we mourn the passing of His majesty, we shall long
remember him for his contributions which strengthened the <ORGANIZATION>United
States-Japan</ORGANIZATION> relationship and set a future course of continued close
and friendly relations,'' the president said.
   Presidential spokesman <PERSON>Marlin Fitzwater</PERSON> said that because there
will be a waiting period before <PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON>'s funeral, the decision on
whom to send would be up to the incoming administration of <PERSON>George
Bush</PERSON>.
   <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> sent letters of condolence to both <PERSON>Hirohito</PERSON>'s son, <PERSON>Akihito</PERSON>,
and the prime minister of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Noboru Takeshita</PERSON>, said <PERSON>Sean Walsh</PERSON>,
a press aide in the vice president's office.
   <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> met the late emperor once on a <DATE>1982</DATE> visit to <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>. Akahito
visited <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> at his home during a trip to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> last
year. The two played tennis together on that occasion.
   <PERSON>Bush</PERSON>'s office did not release the text of the letters. <PERSON>Walsh</PERSON> said
<PERSON>Bush</PERSON> conveyed ``his sincerest condolences'' to Akahito on the death
of his father, and expressed similar sentiments in the letter to the
prime minister.
</TEXT>
